How Tour Prices Developed since 1989
Only five state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia were allowed in 1989: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travellers at that time sold in the vast majority only tours to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled on vacation to the NDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union (Soci in Crimea near the Black Sea), to Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
The light exception was from 1962 to 1972, when the possibility of travelling to Yugoslavia was also possible, but then the Yugoslav regime tended to the West and Czech tourists' journeys to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the time of socialism was that it was not a citizen of the socialist bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovakians) that allowed them to travel individually even within the socialist countries.
If the citizen wanted to travel individually to Poland or to the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter from this country, otherwise an individual journey was not possible.
Travel agencies at that time offered also tours to the West, but it was necessary to stand the front over the night with a sleeping bag or to have a "good-known" in the travel agency.
However, it was not won.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not granted to "politically distrustful people" who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovakian currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, but without foreign exchange promise it was not possible to obtain funds (Western Currency) for the journey to the West.
The most often, however, Czechs spent their vacation in the country, which resulted in a large number of cottages and cottages that the Czechs have acquired and still survives today.
The travel of the Czechs has experienced a real revolution since 1989.
