A huge paradox that we no longer realize today is that it was not possible for us to travel to the most popular Croatia by 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia at that time.
At the end of the 1990s, visa requirements in neighbouring Western European countries were abolished, starting with a huge wave of short-term visits mainly from Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovakians couldn't get enough trips to the West for a while, and everyone wanted to take a look at it for a while.
For example, in Paris, we slept tours of Czechs in parks in tents, because our revenue at that time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or guesthouse.
A typical feature of Czech travel was to carry your own food, canned dishes, salamis, etc. to save yourself.
Another important moment was the introduction of a freely variable Czech crown, so our tourists could finally purchase a Western currency after many decades.
However, our standard of living and with this, average wages rose, resulting in another important moment around 1997.
Due to increased travel demand, travel agents have regularly started preparing charter flights since 1997, thereby making air trips possible to negotiate quantitative discounts compared to the past incredibly cheaper.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs had already had visa-free contacts in virtually all the developed countries of the world, except the US, which continued to facilitate our travel.
