During the first year of government, Maria Lópeze Valdez increased unemployment and instability in Sinaloa, foreign investment and the economy decreased
The year 2011 will be recorded in Sinaloa's economic history. It is the first year of the government of Maria López Valdez, which is called the Government of Change. This government brought great expectations in terms of economic progress, but due to adverse climate conditions at the beginning of the year there was no growth and even a decline in the main indicators of economic development.
Low February temperatures have caused millions of losses in agriculture, reduced the growth potential of the state economy, with a 3.6% reduction in economic activity in the first semester of this year, with a historical decline of 31.16% in agriculture, which has affected the dynamics of other economic sectors.
According to the report on the damage caused by the Mexican Rural Development Council, damage was recorded on 582 835 hectares of the cultivated land, of which 78.03% was completely destroyed and partial damage was found on the remaining 21.07%. The main destroyed crops include vegetables, corn and games.
The decline in economic activity until November caused a constant increase in unemployment in the state. According to the National Institute for Statistics and Geography, the unemployment rate in the State recorded an increase in the first three quarters. From January to March 55 053 inhabitants of the State of Sinaloa were unemployed, representing a unemployment rate of 4.53% of the economically active population. In the second quarter, unemployment increased to 5.28% and between July and August the average unemployment was further increased and reached 6.19%, representing approximately 74,000 unemployed.
Less liquidity
For unemployment during the year in Sinaloa can be more factors. According to Gerard López Cervantes, Director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, it is possible to explain unemployment indirectly, based on the steps taken at public policy level.
"We are witnesses of rising unemployment, which is related to various factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to the reduction of resources due to legislation approved by the Congress in relation to the fight against money laundering. For people who illegally entitle dollars, it is not easy to earn them, invest them or use them for something," he stressed.
Stop Migration
López Cervantes stated that a demographic factor is also involved in the rise in unemployment.
"The number of people who go abroad for work to the United States has fallen, and also because of the difficult entry and then also because these people get abroad, it is difficult for them to get a job, so people stay and demand work from our state, and so unemployment grows," he said.
Insufficiency
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa also worsens because of the growing inconsistencies that prevail in terms of working conditions. According to the National Institute for Statistics and Democracy, 60.38% of the people employed in the State work without taking up social security benefits.
More features of the labour market, such as low wages, are added to unemployment and inconsistencies. In this administrative territory there are the lowest salaries from all over the country, as stated by the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Planning.
The average monthly income of workers in the State of Sinaloa was by September 5 352 peseta, deep below the national average, which runs at an amount of 7 375 pesetas.
Shortening of foreign direct investment
In 2011, the most significant decrease in foreign direct investment over the last 10 years was also recorded, according to the Ministry of Finance from January to June, at a direct foreign investment of $630 697, which represents a fall of 87.74% compared to the amount of $543 312 for the same period of the previous year.
On the other hand, the Ministry of Economic Development of the Government indicates an investment of 17 280 million pesetas per year.
Debt
In the context of the economic downturn scenario, the government asked the State Congress in July to approve a loan of 3 billion peso, which would be intended to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 urban areas in order to revive the economy. The local Congress approved a loan of 2 600 million peso. Until November, no debt gains were recorded, in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
According to representatives of the business sector, the first year of government, Maria López Valdés, pointed out the lack of governance skills.
Miguel Loredo López, Chairman of the National Chamber of Transformative Industry, stated that in 2011 there was no alignment of the will of the individual sectors, including the government itself.
"The development of the economy in Sinaloa has been very small this year. We must work hard to recover the land that we lost this year. In 2012 we have to double our efforts, we lacked harmonisation of our efforts all and, in particular, the correct and synchronized functioning of this new government. Hopefully next year will be much better", he said.
The Slowness of the Economy
Loredo López said that events such as freezing at the beginning of the year stopped the state economy and restricted its development and growth.
"A weak economic movement was caused by a number of events, including freezing. One of the main consequences was the slowdown of the economy, which did not quickly recover enough to restore the dynamics that would allow for an acceptable level of process, product and service movement. Therefore, at the end of the year, we found ourselves deeply below the expected forecasts," he said.
Redefinition of mission
According to Teodore Salazar Uriarte, President of the Employment Confederation of the Republic of Mexico in Sinaloa, it is necessary to push the state towards more dynamic productive activities.
"We are currently seeing that it is working. We believe that we need to prepare a long-term plan in which the objectives and economic direction of the State should be redefined, because it is important to mobilise all the potential of the material and human resources that Sinaloa has," he said.
