The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance has launched a gene that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research to discover the gene responsible for the obesity of children and adolescents.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it conducts research to reveal a gene that causes obesity in children and young people. The research called "Genetics of Obesity in Children and Youth" will allow for results on overweight.
In a report by the Head of the Research Medical Unit in Biochemistry from the Specialised Hospital of the National Health Centre of the 21st century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team composed of doctors, nurses, nutrition professionals and social workers was established.
This team is based on the support of specialists and students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and from the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
People can come to IMSS sports centers in Valle de México, where youth tests will take place every 8 hours.
He stressed that research began at the Cuauhté Power Sports Centre (Mexico State) and since 8 October this activity was also carried out in the Nezahualcoyolt Sports Centre (Mexico State exit).
As soon as data are obtained from 500 to 600 children, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Centre (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Centre (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the objective of this research is to identify the ingredients and the importance of genetics in terms of the development of obesity, and to trace risk factors on Mexican children and young people, thus preventing the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Day of Diabetes, which is celebrated on 14 November, he recalled that the aim is to collect data from 3,000 children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of parents, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or renal insufficiency.
He specified that every Saturday, anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist area) are performed to all participants, blood pressure is measured, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin, and genes are tested (it is designed to identify genes that contribute to the development of child obesity).
Cruz López said that this research reflects health care about the alarming increase in child weight.
'The health surveys carried out between 1999 and 2006 showed that only 77% of the boys and 47% of the girls had been exposed to obesity in just six years. The dramatic increase also occurred in the case of overweight', said an IMSS expert.
He stated that one reason for finding indicators was that the people of the country differed from other populations by their genetic history.
He informed that the average Mexican has 65% Indian-American genetic equipment, 30% European and 5% African. This is reflected in genes that are responsible for developing diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general obesity genetics is commonly explained as inability to burn the excess energy that we consume (calories) and is stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants is that they will receive a overall assessment of the state of their children, which will determine whether they have any known overweight or obesity.
He stated that even the presence of dark-color wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearm suggests the probability of a given individual suffering from metabolic problems and pre-diabetic conditions.
So far, information is confidential, doctors are giving it in writing to their parents and explaining to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they have to make in order to avoid their children's diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: sedentary way of life, meaning a lack of daily physical activity, full-day sitting before television and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
Overweight also causes large calorie intake, it is a greater consumption of sweetened beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and a genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
There will be no extracts in the asphalt from UNAM
Rafael Herrera, a scientist from the UNAM Faculty of Chemicals, creates modified asphalt with polymers, creating a mixture that has better functionality, independent of climate conditions and temperature.
If it were to be properly taken care of, there would not be a need to correct nearly 200 000 extortions after each period of rain in the Metropolitan area of Valle de México, Raphael Herrera Najer, a scientist from the Faculty of Chemicals (FQ) of UNAM, who added that if the construction and maintenance of asphalt pavings were adequate, there would be a significant limitation of the discards, or even could be completely removed.
In his lecture, the Technology Cause of Excesses, which he made during the International Year of Chemistry, announced that the laboratory under his leadership was developing modified asphaltes with polymers, thus creating a mixture of similar characteristics as asphalt, but at the same time greater mechanical resistance, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera Nájer believes that this kind of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely warm climate, for example in some cities in the north of the country, thus improving functionality and reducing the creation of discards.
He explained that asphalt, the most difficult part of oil, is the cluster of hydrocarbons, molecules with a large molecular mass called asphalts, and others with low molecular weights called lactics.
The viscoelastic character of asphalt lies in the fact that, at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it acts as fluid, at 120 degrees it has high viscosity, and at 50 degrees it is almost in solid condition, while at low temperatures it tends to break, added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to meteorological conditions and temperatures, warned the expert on chemical engineering.
A scientist at the Faculty of Chemicals observed that most of the streets in Ciudad de México are covered by a flexible tile consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the top layers is an asphalt liner, made up of small stones covered in asphalt and then compressed.
He stressed that every stone that makes up the insert is covered with asphalt.
When driving cars or while creating pressure, it is possible for forces in the pavement to break well.
If it were a modified asphalt, they would have broken down even better, according to a chemical engineer.
He added that on the asphalt insert, the last layer is called a coat, made up of fine stones, i.e. sand also covered in asphalt.
Since this layer will come into contact with vehicle rims, it must have greater mechanical strength than the asphalt liner and must ensure road friction.
As a part of the paving will be subject to heavy loads, the coat must have sufficient thickness and be careful of the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor that must be remembered. In particular, water has a great influence on the functionality of the asphalt insert.
