Nord Stream, the new Russian gas port in Europe
The Nord Stream remote pipeline, directly connecting Eastern Europe to Russia and led by the bottom of the Baltic Sea, began to work.
It must provide gas equal to the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate this event properly.
More than 500 guests, among them 4 Heads of State and Government, participated last Tuesday in the inauguration of Nord Stream, a new pipeline that will connect directly under the sea Russia and Germany.
symbolically German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch colleague Mark Rutte turned together in control of the Russian gas supply control valve into the West European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion additional cabin gas meters of Russian gas will flow every year through the 1 224 km connecting the St Petersburg region with the Federal Land of Mecklembourg-Pomorans.
The second pipe, which has to be completed at the end of 2012, will allow for the supply of a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, equal to the total French consumption.
And it's already recalled the possibility of building a third pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the early completion of this huge building has the character of victory.
Poland and Baltic countries protested strongly against the project.
Nord Stream actually enables the supply of gas directly to Germany without being led by a third State (Poland or Ukraine).
At the same time, these two countries are losing some power: the possibility of pushing Russia with threats that it will close its access to the Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
Warsaw expressed it most clearly when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the "new German-Soviet Pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
It means that it is a politically sensitive topic.
With its support for this Russian project, Western Europe has gained greater confidence in its purchases.
But it is at the cost of weakening Europe's energy, because the project created cracks between the Eastern and West Europeans.
Russia managed to promote its vision of direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries with high gas consumption, whose bearings are nearing their end, just five years ago.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically links us", confirmed François Fillon at the ceremony of opening this pipeline and demonstrated at what point the major gas contracts of things are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles of the leaders of Gazprom, who are present in the large number of Lubmin, the gas feeder.
The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical act.
The submarine pipe is of steel provided with a concrete shell in order to protect against the anchors of marine vessels.
It lies at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction, it was necessary to avoid minefields originating from World War II.
"For safety, almost a hundred had to be removed or destroyed", says Jens Müller, spokesperson of Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing 242 the Eiffel, which is not interrupted anywhere by valves or maintenance stations over its entire length.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project manager rejected it when the Swedes were only a little eager to see the Russian state company, as it was permanently settled off their coasts.
"In the event of a failure, we will stop the gas passage in less than 1 minute", explains Jens Müller.
In the case of leakage, the gas contained in the gas pipeline shall be released into the air.
But this case is considered to be unlikely by the builder, for welds were designed to cause leakage once every 100,000 years.
The control of the external gas pipeline is carried out by an underwater robot towed ships, while the inside of the gas pipeline is controlled by a device that circulations inside.
This device of a cigar shape with a diameter of 1 m is introduced into the inside of the pipe and is pushed by the gas.
In the target, 3 m/s speed for all three days, it shall provide accurate information on possible distortions of metallic parts.
The remote gas pipeline was designed to function for 50 years without needing a minor repair.
Gas circulation is simply secured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar in the finish.
Five companies joined forces for the implementation of this project.
Gazprom, who holds 51%, remains in charge.
It was joined by the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, commissioned by the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company has its registered office in the town of Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely favourable.
Gazprom subsequently leased this company for five years by the Treaty which can be renewed, all its capacity for the transport of gas.
"Gazprom will profit from the overall capacity, whether the amount of real gas is any", explains Jens Müller.
The financing of the gas pipeline was ensured by 30% of the shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total labour costs should be €7.4 billion for both pipes.
The investment costs for GDF Suez increased to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure that their costs will be returned to them, since only Gazprom takes the risk.
Gas pipeline comes from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on the sandy coast with pine forests.
The vents are 4,5 metres high, forming the exit gate of the gas.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transported to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives one million Cuban meters of Russian gas every hour.
With full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012 6 million.
